That’s the right final piece. You can keep the interaction layer very lightweight—enough for a working demo without adding heavy frameworks.

Here’s a **minimal, accessible accordion pattern** that fits the playbook style:

```html
<!-- HTML -->
<section class="accordion">
  <h2>
    <button class="accordion-trigger"
            aria-expanded="false"
            aria-controls="panel1"
            id="accordion1">
      Engage / Validate
    </button>
  </h2>
  <div id="panel1" role="region" aria-labelledby="accordion1" hidden>
    <p>I hear how painful this feels; you're not alone.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>
    <button class="accordion-trigger"
            aria-expanded="false"
            aria-controls="panel2"
            id="accordion2">
      Ground
    </button>
  </h2>
  <div id="panel2" role="region" aria-labelledby="accordion2" hidden>
    <p>Let's take a slow breath together...</p>
  </div>
</section>
```

```css
/* Basic styling */
.accordion-trigger {
  width: 100%;
  text-align: left;
  padding: var(--space-md);
  font-family: var(--font-header);
  font-size: var(--font-size-header);
  border: none;
  background-color: var(--color-calm);
  color: var(--color-text-light);
  cursor: pointer;
}
.accordion-trigger[aria-expanded="true"] {
  background-color: var(--color-action);
}
[role="region"] {
  padding: var(--space-md);
  background-color: var(--color-neutral);
}
```

```js
// Minimal JS
const triggers = document.querySelectorAll('.accordion-trigger');
triggers.forEach(btn => {
  btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
    const expanded = btn.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true';
    btn.setAttribute('aria-expanded', !expanded);
    const panel = document.getElementById(btn.getAttribute('aria-controls'));
    panel.hidden = expanded;
  });
});
```

**Notes**

- Uses semantic `<button>` for keyboard navigation.  
- `aria-expanded` toggles automatically; screen readers announce state change.  
- The `hidden` attribute keeps non‑active panels out of focus order.  
- Add smooth transitions (`max-height`, `overflow:hidden`) for polish if desired.

This snippet, your CSS variables, and the content modules together create a clean, accessible interactive prototype that mirrors the printed playbook.

