That’s exactly the right place to end the package: the progressive‑enhancement fallback guarantees that even if JavaScript fails, the information still appears and screen readers can use it.

Here’s the **pure‑CSS backup pattern**:

```html
<section class="accordion-fallback">
  <h2><label for="engage">Engage / Validate</label></h2>
  <input type="checkbox" id="engage" hidden>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>I hear how painful this feels; you're not alone.</p>
  </div>

  <h2><label for="ground">Ground</label></h2>
  <input type="checkbox" id="ground" hidden>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Let's take a slow breath together...</p>
  </div>
</section>
```

```css
/* Pure‑CSS accordion using checkboxes */
.accordion-fallback label {
  display: block;
  background: var(--color-calm);
  color: var(--color-text-light);
  padding: var(--space-md);
  cursor: pointer;
}
.panel {
  max-height: 0;
  overflow: hidden;
  transition: max-height 0.3s ease;
  background: var(--color-neutral);
  padding: 0 var(--space-md);
}
input[type="checkbox"]:checked + .panel {
  max-height: 10em;
  padding: var(--space-md);
}
```

A browser with JavaScript turned off will still display the full content when each checkbox is toggled, and assistive technology will read the labels correctly.

